Looking around, you notice that you are on the edge of a steep cliff. To the south, the road is blocked by a pile of boulders. To the west, an unclimbable cliff rises up above you. according to the spec, z-index should not work on SVG elements (except possibly a positioned <svg> element with non-SVG parent) everyone agrees we need to change SVG to support some form of z-index jwatt and I have argued pretty hard that we should support CSS z-index directly, with stacking contexts etc other people have argued that CSS z-index stacking contexts are not necessary for SVG Then SVG elements with z-index not 'auto' would be positioned but not create a stacking context for their descendants which would be weird I mean positioned in z-order Webkit and Firefox are just following the current spec one reason to want stacking contexts for SVG is that you want 'opacity' and 'filter' and other effects to induce a stacking context no otherwise you get weirdness like a blur filter applied to an element subtree, but the element's children are not all part of the same rendering group because there's another non-blurred element in between and then it becomes really unclear what the rendered results should be, or how to produce them that's true, but doesn't help us here, I think

http://www.tbray.org/ongoing/When/200x/2009/04/29/Model-and-Syntax - "I have long believed and repeatedly written that bits on the wire are the only serious reliable basis for interoperability, and worried in public about the feasibility of shared models" That seems kind of completely opposite to the HTML 5 philosophy, which is that the document model is the important thing, and the bits on the wire are just one of many ways of serialising the model wonders how the connect the different viewpoints b25b6b77a0087ff8385941e5545d32ea: But the main basis for interoperability is the rules for how UAs process the document model, and isn't just about the syntax unlike XML, which is defined as purely syntax (and that purely syntactic definition causes problems with e.g. when do you execute <script>s while parsing XHTML, so the model is valuable too) It still seems true that bits-on-the-wire are important by themselves - people think of HTML and XML as character strings, and that's a useful and successful view, and we'd lose that if we just had the DOM API and some unreadable custom binary protocol for transferring DOMs Test-driven development I suppose the focus on bits-on-the-wire vs document models could also be blamed for e.g. RSS readers that just use regexps to interpret those bits Maybe the bits-on-the-wire view is more useful during the early stages of a protocol, when we want to encourage competition between widely varying ways of implementing and using the protocol; but as the technology matures, the dominant document model should be specified and standardised, to improve interoperability Maybe RSS->Atom could be seen the same way? can't think of any other examples... I don't quite see why that's relevant Someone could define a processing model for XML that turns a stream of bytes into a DOM or Infoset or SAX stream or whatever, and that'd solve the questions about when scripts execute and how document.write could be fitted in etc, but they don't seem to have done that yet (and draconity doesn't have anything to do with that, as far as I can tell) (There's also things like Jabber which rely somewhat on the processing model of XML parsers, e.g. elements should be reported as soon as their close tag's '>' is seen) goes away for a bit

Evidently not. 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e, "not a vulnerability by itself " MediaWiki, for instance, doesn't escape anything before storing in the DB, as a rule. It trusts text content in the DB as untrusted. All escaping is done as close to output time as possible, so it's easy to audit. It's much harder to escape at input time, since input can come from a zillion different places that you have varying degrees of control over. Then what vulnerability is there? By "output" I mean "use". 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e, store it in the database as an unsigned integer?  :) But okay. "not validating user input" I don't know of a way to phrase it positively (without "failing", "not", etc.) "Input validation" is definitely the term for the thing you should be doing. For the thing you shouldn't be doing, "improper input validation" sounds like as good a term as any. It's not an exploit by itself, so it doesn't get a buzzword. Well, I guess it can be a minor exploit by itself. Like if you have maxlength and users can just remove it in their favorite web development tool and submit stuff that's whatever length they want, that might be classified as a security vulnerability, insofar as it involves users doing something with your site that they aren't supposed to be able to. ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c, Wikipedia was actually hit by a subtle version of that once. Squid did understand X-Forwarded-For and sanitized it, but the PHP variables used to access it treated X_Forwarded_For the same as X-Forwarded-For, and Squid didn't. MediaWiki has a whitelist of trusted XFF providers that it uses, including various major ISPs in addition to its own internal Squids and Varnishes. It's kind of vague. Basically "modified", yeah. Are you sure you are using the proper collections? table.tBodies[i].rows[j].cells[k] ? CAiRO: There cant be undefined elements. There can be whitespace nodes, but if you hit them you are doing stuff wrong CAiRO: Tables are extremely well suported with references. Use them CAiRO: now why would you even traverse the table like that? What is it you are trying to do? There is absolutely no need to check the tagname if you do it right This still doesnt explain why you are traversing every element CAiRO: So you only need to work on the table rows, correct? ok then for (var i = 0; i < table.rows.length; i++) { if (table.rows[i].cells[0].className == 'something') do something else; } CAiRO: You need to take advantage of the allready existing collections CAiRO: Each table has a tHead, a tBodies collection and a tFoot Each of these have their own rows collection that in turn have each their own cells collection I might need to write an article about how well supported tables are someday. People seem to not know about it CAiRO: omg. You are also using for..in. Dont b0at: Using the builtin collections are faster since you dont need to query the DOM It's not much, but when the reference is allready there I dont see the need to do DOM queries CAiRO: for/in is for iterating an objects properties. You want to use for(;;) to iterate through enoumerated properties of an array or collection table.tBodies[0] It's there CAiRO: Thats how it is. If it feels wrong, it probably is ;) CAiRO: They might either be: 1) whitespace nodes. 2) object properties that you iterated through because of your wrong for/in usage CAiRO: The childNodes collection includes whitespacenodes in gecko Anyway, the practicality of the builtin collections and methods like getElementsByTagName should be clear to you now

that doesn't make a lot of sense from a conceptual point of view at least. it sounds like you're doing a table, so why not make your divs table-cell instead or at least, a table-row I don't know whether this theme offers some way to do this, but generally the idea of a float "filling the remaining horizontal space" makes no sense, because it's an inline element. it already fills the remaining space, because the content space ends with the last float there is. Much like trying to get a <span> to fill "the rest of the line". The line ends where it ends. It might be possible with some really creative tinkering, but I don't know of a way to do so. I do know that it's a good idea to stay away from floats for content blocks that need to be aware of their surroundings. could svg change here? ... would like to modify the svg parser to accept css syntax for transforms, so e.g translate(20px, 20px) would be supported rik: that's a big change dirk: you have to use units in css syntax anyway rik: but for an svg parser not having a css parser? dirk: that's why i'm proposing extended to allow the css syntax, but without requiring a full css parser ... if we change transform to be a presentation attribute it's still a property b5f3729e5418905ad2b21ce186b1c01d: the current presentation attributes are still parsed as defined in svg, but we've discussed allowing css syntax (and parsing) in svg attributes sorry, now missing things due to speaking and scribing at the same time :) dirk: i also wanted to suggest aryeh gregor as an b5f3729e5418905ad2b21ce186b1c01ditor for the merged transforms spec cl: is he member of css or svg wg? dirk: he's a member of csswg ACTION: dirk to contact all the b5f3729e5418905ad2b21ce186b1c01ditors of http://dev.w3.org/csswg/css3-transforms/ to see if they agree to have Aryeh Gregor as an b5f3729e5418905ad2b21ce186b1c01ditor too, and send a mail to public-fx about it looks through http://www.w3.org/Graphics/SVG/WG/wiki/SVG2_Requirements_Input CL: smfr claimed 2d transforms is css only, not fx ... pointed out that svg had had transforms much longer, but people didn't want to slow down rik: the 2d spec, not the combined one? cl: also concerns about where bugs were tracked ... csswg wants to push ahead with 2d transforms ... perhaps driven by the prefix discussions CC: canon was interested in having 3d transforms in svg ... we were happy with it being a combined spec ... but don't want it to be css only ... it needs to work in svg dirk: currently working on the merged transforms spec, we're mostly clear on transform-origin e.g ... there's no conclusion from the minutes CL pasted that says the csswg will continue with the 2d transforms independently CL: the minutes are a bit partial, vincent argued that we should work together ... and there are issues with the spec still ... some issues joint between 2d and 3d ... we should discuss this in Hamburg CC: from the minutes, david says "I don't want to wait on 2d stuff", and svg has had transforms for 10-12 years, don't understand why css would have to wait for svg ... would be fine with transform with only 2d that is compatible with svg, and later one spec with 3d with support for svg as well CL: would be good to have proposed resolutions for the Hamburg meeting dirk: mayube the 3d stuff won't be ready, but 2d should be possible ... pretty sure we'll have a working draft to hamburg, 3d included CC: simon says he was createing tests for 3d transforms CL: some concerns from simon in the CSSWG meeting about testing transforms, but svg has had this tested for a long time ... should be possible to just take tests from svg rik: seems many things went unminuted in the csswg meeting dirk: can we resolve that svg will use css-like parsing rules? CL: what would it say exactly? b5f3729e5418905ad2b21ce186b1c01d: we can resolve things on the public-fx mailinglist, if enough people respond to the thread dirk: only thing missing is that svg supports scientific notation for numbers b5f3729e5418905ad2b21ce186b1c01d: ok, let's try and resolve this on the list Topic: issue-66 http://dev.w3.org/SVG/proposals/css-animation/animation-proposal.html b5f3729e5418905ad2b21ce186b1c01d: previous discussions indicated that this should be made a spec module on top of svg 1.1, and perhaps later included in svg2 dirk: i could be co b5f3729e5418905ad2b21ce186b1c01ditor cl: we need someone from MS to take this on b5f3729e5418905ad2b21ce186b1c01d: i could also co b5f3729e5418905ad2b21ce186b1c01dit ... we need more feedback from the csswg, i did send this to www-style, but we might need to get this on the wg's agenda too present+ 227a9a17d1db3f8e5c71a150345fb2a6 ACTION: b5f3729e5418905ad2b21ce186b1c01d to contact Microsoft about ISSUE-66, and b5f3729e5418905ad2b21ce186b1c01ditorship, and to mail the csswg chairs about the syntax issues for svgattrs->cssprops 22813b6f9b851d152e2f2d99116de592, end telcon

scribenick: 4f7b888020097eaa802a99e757c6dad7 Topic: system colors Richard is presenting Richard, IBM accessibility richard  will explain why it is not a good idea to deprecate system clolors R: with rich internet apps, we can create objects that use system color settings like "icon", "menu" etc. R: while system colors are available, accessibility can find colors and get idea of a role DB is trying to understand why we are talking about using things that look like system controls but are not system controls R: actually it is to keep application colors in sync with system settings. e.g. if there is a system color for highlight it can be applied to tree widgets Hakon: do you know about personal stylesheet DB: does is have to lead to CSS system colors as a solution? Elika: ... ways to override colors based on Aria settings DB: points at the titlebar with a gradient in windows colors dialog DB: css system colors model system effect, but in a simpler way, as a set of colors rather than exact system effects like rounded borders or gradients DB: that is a big rationale for deprecation (colors don't represent exact system effect) DB: another rationale - these are very Windows specific DB: Windows controls are used in controls in multiple combinations that are hard to map to other systems ... more discussion JD: I'm concerned that we're going for checking items off a list rather than actually solving the problem Richard: My concern is mainly about giving the author the ability to ensure enough contrast. Richard: My suggestion is to pick a baseline set of colors: window bg, text color, highlight colors, and maybe a border color and draw the line there. Howcome: Can I show you what we do with Opera? Howcome projects Opera with high-contrast settings. DB: There are other ways to do this besides style sheets DB: Mozilla has the minimum size pref DB: We also have options to say that the browser should ignore colors set by the author. DB: When we do that, we also preserve transparency, which you can't do with an author style sheet. DB: When you start doing things like that, then you get to the point where a lot of applications will still work. DB: Even if you make government websites meet these requirements, users are going to want to visit other sites as well. DB: You have the option of solving the problem at one point, and you have the option of making all authors try to solve the problem. SZ: So what I'm hearing is that system colors doesn't solve the problem. SZ: Maybe the way of solving the problem is identifying ways the browser can enable a disabled person to view the web SZ: The catch is that the browser is only one aspect of using the computer. SZ: With system colors, the settings are system-wide DB: When you turn off author colors, usually the browser will use the system colors as the default. DB: The point I was making a few minutes ago, it seems when there's the possibility of solving this problem at one point vs. making each author solve them independently DB: It seems we're going for the high-cost approach. Richard: The browser doesn't know what the author intended. DB: I'm not saying that the approach I want would mean no work for the author. DB: For example, the author might have to use appropriate markup to cause the browser to do the right thing. Richard: That works for standard form controls. Richard: But when the author is making custom controls, the author needs to make the decisions the browser makes EE: Couldn't you make the browser style custom controls based on the ARIA attributes? EE: If the author uses the ARIA attributes correctly (which you're assuming anyway) then the browser can have a setting that forces system colors on those controls based on the ARIA attributes. EE: I note that if you make the authors do the coloring work, most of them will get it wrong. Howcome shows Opera's high-contrast and zoom settings on Yahoo Mail richard point at selection not being visible at yahoo inbox JD: how would system colors help here? Richard: because it uses highlight colors of the system EE: aria attributes have enough information to be able to render with the right colors AM: Aria has coarser granularity, not enough to represent UI elements discussing tabs on Orange page example... DB: tabs are really really complicated. questioning if system colors will help EE: browser shoud be able to make things look like tabs... AM is not sure what it means Hakon reminds about mobile

Alex: So what I'm hearing is that you want system colors so that someone who has the budget to really do a lot of accessibility work they can make a really cool-looking app with system colors EE: System colors don't give you access to the gradients, bitmaps, etc. that you need to make a modern-looking app EE: If you want to use system colors, sure you can get enough contrast EE: But your web app will look like a Windows 3.1 application EE: That's the best you can do with system colors EE: The browser can get access to all of that stylistic information and draw real-looking controls EE: If it has a way of knowing what to draw where Richard: ... Richard: I'm proposing that you have four basic colors so you can draw controls with enough contrast Peter: That won't be enough DB: I'd like to point out that deprecated doesn't mean gone. DB: Deprecated means there's a better solution DB: It might be not quite ready yet, but this is not the right permanent solution Richard: What's the better solution? DB: Some combination of better markup for controls and the CSS 'appearance' property EE: Deprecation means they shouldn't be used in favor of something else (the 'appearance' property), but they are still required to be supported. DB: Mozilla has supported system colors for ages. PL: It uses them to render its own UI, so it has more capability for representing system-based UI than is in that spec Richard: So I'd request that you add that wording to css3-color DB: I've added it to my issues list Richard: And we need to come up with a solution JD: I think it needs to be at a higher semantic level SZ: It would be nice if css3-color linked informatively to the 'appearance' property discussion about custom controls, HTML5, system colors, accessibility, etc Richard: lotus Notes 4 had 200 custom controls ... Richard: So you're saying that these colors are supported in IE, Opera, Mozilla, and WebKit? DB: more or less DB: but I've had to go through and write implementation reports for these DB: and I couldn't mark them all as passing DB: Each time it was some bizarre judgement call DB: about whether the system color approximated what it was supposed to approximate DB: whether or not that thing existed on the OS I was running the test on

QA definition of deprecated: http://www.w3.org/QA/glossary "An existing feature that has become outdated and is in the process of being phased out, usually in favor of a specified replacement. Deprecated features are no longer recommended for use and may cease to exist in future versions of the specification."

anyone who makes a distinction between HTML5 and HTML 5 (with/without space) as referring to the serialisation and vocabularly, respectively, is wrong. The distiction can only be made based on context or, where it's not entirely clear, by explicitly qualifying it as, e.g., "HTML5 syntax" or "HTML5 vocabularly" the spec is wrong While it might be nice in theory to have such a distinction, in reality, we don't because we can't make people use them consistently there was a big discussion about this a year or two ago, with many people wanting to find an alternative name for it. We had all sorts of weird and wonderful suggestions like calling the serialisation "tHTML", which was short for text/html or something well, I guess it's not really wrong. It's a useful convention for the spec to adhere too. But it's not something it can really enforce outside of the spec

Question about the media API: Seeking works by setting currentTime to a new value (in seconds). Is there a special reason why currentTime isn't readonly and seeking works e.g. with a method seek(), taking a relative value (zero to one), which would cover the case when the duration of the stream isn't known (but it's filesize is) and rough seeking shall still be available. s/./? (there are media formats without a header containing duration, so all you got is the byte position if the client shouldn't try to find a timestamp at the end of the bytestream) yeah, if the duration in "proper time" isn't known one can still seek to an approximate position using the position of the bytestream this, however, only works if seeking is not taking absolute time. The client can then find a fitting representation if duration is known: Seek to the position (in seconds or whatever) if only the length of the bytestream is known: Well, just jump to a position in there I'm currently trying to implement a subset of the HTML5 media specs for a Java playback applet, which only knows bytepositions and thus always seeks relative I *could* estimate the total duration in seconds given the current byteposition and the current timestamp the media stream has but that means the duration will change during playback (and given how dynamic video bitrate is this estimate can be like 1000% off) (the estimate will first be horrible and be more accurate at the end) this isn't just specific to this applet thingie, but for some formats the clients really have to seek to the end of the file and find a timestamp befor the duration is known ah, I see :) same solution as for my applet ;-) most won't quite frankly I'd hope that currentTime would be currentPosition, which can either be seconds *or* byte position and a flag indicating what it is same for duration but this smells like a hack right http://people.xiph.org/ 99a3bfa1a9430e7df6358b5f3e9e1e17/demos/bigbuckbunny-applet.html <-- applet without duration given. Will still allow seeking (relative to byteposition) and display a progress bar (also byteposition). Works out okay in practice sweet dreams! and yeah, will write a mail (my proposals on relative seeking: http://lists.whatwg.org/pipermail/whatwg-whatwg.org/2008-November/017387.html ) (oh, 040342c014ffc1c11592948bd92e3721 did leave the room)

acceptCount is the server socket accept queue. The threads are in a thread pool. The pool is populated with minSpareThreads threads first. Then Tomcat starts serving requests. If it finds that all threads are being used, it starts to create more threads and add them to the pool (*while* trying to serve requests.. sometimes that's a bad idea). It will create more threads for the thread pool up to the maxThreads limit. Once it reaches maxThreads, that's as many as it will create, regardless of the traffic load. Whenever the load decreases, Tomcat tries to determine if it still needs as many threads as it has instantiated and running. If it knows it doesn't need them all, it ends some threads to decrease the count in the pool. It will decrease them until it reaches the lower bound of minSpareThreads again. It can keep going up and down like that, creating and then ending threads while serving requests, as long as there is diff between minSpareThreads and maxThreads. So, on busy servers where you already know that you'll usually want it to hang out at maxThreads, you should set minSpareThreads and maxThreads to the same value so that it never spends CPU time going up and down with the thread count. No, it will only give a client a connection refused message if the accept queue is smaller than the number of waiting incoming client socket connections that have not yet been assigned a thread from the thread pool. The client sockets sit in the accept queue waiting for a thread.  Once one is free in the thread pool, it is taken out of the accept queue and assigned the thread. caverdude: Yes. But, if there are no threads available in the pool to assign to the client socket, the client sockets stack up in the accept queue, waiting. If too many stack up in there, you'll exceed your acceptCount value, and the very next request socket will get a connection refused message. So, it's generally a good idea to set the queue size larger, and then make sure that they never stack up that high in the queue by making sure there are enough threads to handle the load. Actually, setting the accept queue high doesn't really impact how slow response times are. It's how available request processor threads are. I don't actually know good reasons for setting the accept queue size low.  :) I guess setting accept count lower will have the effect of intentionally "spilling" some of the traffic off of your server so it won't be so crushed under the load.. but most people find it unacceptable for a web site to give a connection refused message.  :) jmonstad: I'd set the accept count higher.  IIRC the limit is 255?  Or something like that.  I'd set it to 200.  You have nothing to lose. Right. That just makes performance worse. Same with the JVM memory settings -Xmx and -Xms.. make the exactly the same number so that it never needs to change. jmonstad: You're welcome.  I think I documented some of this in the O'Reilly Tomcat book (first edition, so far). jmonstad: Other than that, you're not likely to find much info about it anywhere except on the tomcat-dev mailing list, and even then it may not be easily readable. It's somewhat outdated now, but I'm updating it, and the second edition will be out early '07. Lots of the explanatory text in there still does apply though. If you hang out in this channel, and ask periodically, I'm sure there are people who could help with that. It does help. The book really isn't that expensive, and it's packed with zillions of answers that you'd otherwise have to spend your time ( = money!) searching for the answers. The book has lots of plain english text about how things work. Okay, you're welcome. See ya.

I see I'm pinged. I don't want to be put in a position of responding defensively, which the tone of the above steers me to. I also have a meeting in a few so can't really get into it. A couple points of information: The PF comments list is post-only because if comments come to a list where discussion also happens, it's nearly impossible to verify that we've satisfied our formal requirement of responding to all comments if they're mixed in with discussion. So we define comments as those arriving on the post-only list, and other discussions are helpful but not treated formally. We do participate in discussions about the issues that have been submitted to us, included the XTech list, HTML list, and other fora. None of those discussions necessarily represent a group consensus on how to respond to the comment. Ensuring we have consensus on the response is one reason we hold off on sending responses. The discussion of the public comments is happening in Member space in part because PF is structured as a Member group and that is the visibility our tracker happens to have. I have to say, though, that discussing more openly, when the discussion isn't complete and we don't have consensus, sometimes triggers a flood of reactions that we have to take time to deal with, when we didn't even have... ...consensus on the position, so it really makes it difficult for us to fulfill our process requirements. The comment stage does include a phase of requesting feedback from the commenter. We don't simply publish a new draft after rejecting suggestions received, without at least working with the commenter to see if we can arrive at a position. We were not under formal requirements to respond to comments received before Last Call, so have not violated Process. However, we did make an attempt to make sure we addressed things. It is quite possible we dropped the ball on some, and I apologize. Please don't send comments to wai-xtech without sending to public-pfwg-comments. They won't get processed as formal comments. Discussions on wai-xtech are helpful, and we'll try to be sure to reference them as we discuss the comments. I have to go to a meeting now. I hope this is helpful information. I feel like you think we're acting in bad faith, and I believe we're working very hard to act in good faith. We have specific reasons for the way we do things, I hope you can understand that. yes, but I wrote it just now, it wasn't a canned response if that's what you're asking I'm sorry, I am in a meeting now, I can't continue discussion right now. It does seem re last comment that this is a larger issue with concerns about W3C process. I feel caught in the middle on that. I really can't address it right now, and suggest we need Team discussion on this. FWIW I've been supporting many of the POVs expressed by HTML members in various fora but also have various constraints to work in

it's in Xtables-addons mostly. ipaddr is not, but ECHO for example is. anyway, xtables-addons provides enough simple skeletal code to be reused. if you use the git repository, you can switch to the "IPMARK" branch which should provide a somewhat simpler target git://dev.computergmbh.de/xtables-addons and /xtables main page (http://dev.computergmbh.de/) says "Clone URL" :-) i'll add ipaddr into a separate branch Netfilter is the whole thing; Xtables is one specific hook for Netfilter; Connection Tracking is another hook for Netfilter; and the NAT engine is another hook for Netfilter. so much for the kernel side on the userspace side, iptables/xtables is the package with the user tool.
